***********************
* Java Bittorrent API *
***********************

Author: Baptiste Dubuis, Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, EPFL

Version: 1.2

Webpage: http://sourceforge.net/projects/bitext/

Note: The sources have been reorganised under the net.sourceforge.bitext.* package
   namespace (bittorrent / tracker / utils) and a set of client extension points has
   been added (pluggable piece storage and per-peer/torrent access control). See
   README-jBittorrentAPI ("Extensibility") and README-tracketBT for details.

Description:

   The Java Bittorrent API project aims at providing a simple and easy-to-use API
   for future work on Bittorrent protocol. It provides classes and methods that 
   permit to complete each step necessary to publish files and retrieve them 
   using the Bittorrent network.

   The goal is to provide any user the possibility to share files with other 
   people without having to bother too much.
   
   In this scope, this project propose a bittorrent tracker that can be run to 
   accept files for sharing. This tracker is part of the trackerBT package.

   Provided also is a bittorrent API that permit to publish files using 
   bittorrent protocol, as much as to download files from other people. This 
   API is part of the jBittorrentAPI package.

   - To publish files using bittorrent protocol, user have to follow these steps:
      - Create a new torrent file which will provide information about the 
        target files the user wants to publish and make available to others.
        This can be done by running the ExampleCreateTorrent program.
      - Publish this torrent file on a tracker so that other people can have 
        access to the desription of the target files and then be able to 
        download them. This is done by running the ExamplePublish program.
      - Share the local target files to permit people to download files from
        local directory. This is done by running the ExampleShareFiles program.

   - To download files from other people, user have to get the torrent file from 
     any tracker or web server and then run the ExampleDownloadFiles program.
   For further instruction on how to use either the trackerBT or jBittorrentAPI 
   packages, please read the corresponding README files:

   For convenience, an example is provided to demonstrate the use of these program
   step by step. Please read the README-example for further information.


Building with Maven:

   A Maven build is provided (pom.xml). It compiles every source under src/
   (both the jBittorrentAPI client and the trackerBT tracker) and produces a
   single self-contained ("fat") jar. A Maven Wrapper (./mvnw, pinned to Maven
   3.9.9) is included so the same Maven is used locally, in CI, and on JitPack:

      ./mvnw clean package        (or: mvn clean package)

   This creates target/jbittorrentapi-ext-1.2.jar, which bundles the
   only runtime dependencies the tracker needs (JDOM, the legacy Simple 3.x HTTP
   server, and kXML). The client half uses no third-party libraries. The build
   targets Java 8 bytecode (the source requires at least Java 7 due to NIO.2 in
   the file manager). Run, for example:

      java -cp target/jbittorrentapi-ext-1.2.jar \
           net.sourceforge.bitext.tracker.Tracker example_tracker_config.xml

   The vendored dependencies live in a small in-repo Maven repository
   (maven-repo/) because the legacy Simple 3.x server is not published on Maven
   Central. The classic manual build (javac -cp "../ext/*" ...) described in the
   other README files still works too.

Publishing to GitHub Packages:

   The artifact is published to GitHub Packages
   (https://maven.pkg.github.com/crewmanmud/jbittorrentapi-ext).

   - Automated: publishing a GitHub Release (or running the "Publish to GitHub
     Packages" workflow manually) deploys the artifact via
     .github/workflows/publish.yml.
   - Manual: add a <server> with id "github" to ~/.m2/settings.xml, using your
     GitHub username and a personal access token with the write:packages scope,
     then run:

        mvn deploy

Consuming the library:

   Published coordinate (both channels): com.github.crewmanmud:jbittorrentapi-ext

   Option A - JitPack (anonymous, no credentials):

      <repositories>
        <repository>
          <id>jitpack.io</id>
          <url>https://jitpack.io</url>
        </repository>
      </repositories>

      <dependency>
        <groupId>com.github.crewmanmud</groupId>
        <artifactId>jbittorrentapi-ext</artifactId>
        <version>1.2</version>
      </dependency>

   JitPack builds the project on first request from the matching git tag and
   caches the result (see jitpack.yml). For pre-release testing you can use a
   branch build such as "main-SNAPSHOT" or a commit hash as the <version>.

   Option B - GitHub Packages (requires authentication, even for reads):

      <repositories>
        <repository>
          <id>github</id>
          <url>https://maven.pkg.github.com/crewmanmud/jbittorrentapi-ext</url>
        </repository>
      </repositories>

      <dependency>
        <groupId>com.github.crewmanmud</groupId>
        <artifactId>jbittorrentapi-ext</artifactId>
        <version>1.2</version>
      </dependency>

   GitHub Packages requires a <server id="github"> in ~/.m2/settings.xml with
   your GitHub username and a token holding the read:packages scope.

   Because the artifact is a self-contained ("fat") jar, neither option pulls any
   transitive dependencies.


